Linear Mixed Effects Models

  • We will now discuss and implement a framework of models called generalized linear models, or linear mixed effect models.
  • Before we get into the mathematical details, lets step back and think about the goals of regression and how they are accomplished with standard general linear models.
  • There is some underlying data generating process.
  • We wish to make inference about this underlying data generating process, based on data we have observed.
  • We summarize our inference on the data generating process through the parameter estimates in the model.
  • Lets use the hypothetical example of mortality rates at hospitals.
    • We have measured mortality rates on multiple hospitals from last year.
    • The hospitals have varying numbers of patients. Some are small (so we have less information about those hospitals), some are large (so we have more information about those hospitals).
    • If we look at last years mortality rates for each hospital, some have a higher mortality rate, and some have a lower mortality rate.
    • Lets think about why there was differences in mortality rates in the first place! Is it because some hospitals give better or worse care (a true hospital level difference)? Or was it just random variationthe bad hospitals had an unlucky year, and the good hospitals had a lucky year?
    • How can we use last years mortality rates to identify which are bad and which are good hospitals?
    • Or stated differentlyhow can we use data from last year to identify the TRUE underlying mortality rate at each hospital?
    • Take a moment to try to come up with a few different ideas.

Hospital Mortality

In order to understand this class of models, lets first consider the problem of trying to identify hospital mortality amongst a bunch of different hospitals . Consider that the hospitals are all different sizes; we have small hospitals, and large hospitals. In addition to having different sizes the hospitals have very different mortality rates. If your task is to identify who is a good hospital, and who is about hospital, how would you go about doing it?

Hospital Mortality

We could start by simply calculating the mortality rates and ranking the hospitals from best to worst based on their observed rate. This is what we do When we fit linear regression that youve already learned about. We call these fixed effects, which means we dont share any information between the hospitals. We assume all the information we have about a single hospital is contained only within the data from that hospital . There is no information sharing between hospitals .

  • Is that reasonable?

  • Have you ever heard of the phrase regression to the mean?

Hospital Mortality

An alternative approach is to try to share information between the hospitals. Basically, we are saying that even if a hospital has a really bad mortality rate, or a really good mortality rate , that is probably not their true rate. Their true rate is closer to the average, and they just had a good or a bad year.

Random Effects Versus Fixed Effects

  • Fixed Effects
    • This is what you are familiar with from prior modeling experience. Everything was a fixed effect!
    • All information for that effect is held within the level of that effect
    • There is no sharing of information across groups
    • Makes sense for categorical variables with a few unique levels
    • Gender, SES, smoking status
  • Random Effects
    • Information from other levels should be shared to make inference for this effect
    • Regression to the mean
    • Categorical variables with lots of levels
    • Person ID, Hospital, Clinician, things that are clusters

Benefits of Random Effects

  • Potentially increased model accuracy. The shrinkage effect that comes from sharing information across levels gives us better (less biased) model estimates.
  • Less degrees of freedom
  • Assumption of independence violations may be fixed with a random effect. Remember the assumption of homogeneity?
  • We can quantify the width of variation within clusters. The actual random effects themselves may be of interest.
  • We can compare the within cluster variation to the residual variation
  • We accomplish this through additional variance components in the model (not additional fixed effects)

Model Formulation

\[E(Y) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k} + e\]

  • The traditional linear model formula includes an outcome, fixed effects with betas, and an error term.
  • The addition of the random effects is often represented like below, with Z gamma as the random effects piece.
  • We will not focus on the linear algebra here, but it is important to recall we are working with matrices.
  • We could rewrite this considering X as a matrix, and Beta as a vector in our notation:

\[E(Y) = \mathbf B*\mathbf X + e\]

  • Now we will add another component for the random effects, typically noted as the Z matrix:

\[E(Y) = \mathbf X\mathbf \beta + \mathbf Z\mu + e\]

MathAchieve Data

  • The outcome we will focus on is math scores. School will be our potential random effect.
  • Lets examine the distribution of the average math scores by school to see if that is a large source of variation.
## aggregate dataset
school_avg <- 
  MathAchieve_dt[,list(MatchAchMean=mean(MathAch)),by=School]

## Create a plot showing the overall variation and school variation
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(MathAchieve_dt,aes(x=MathAch)) +
  geom_histogram() + xlim(c(-10,30))

ggplot(school_avg,aes(x=MatchAchMean)) +
  geom_histogram() + xlim(c(-10,30))

  • It certainly looks like some schools have higher test scores, while others have lower test scores.
  • The width of the histogram (the amount of variance by school) is pretty wide compared to the original histogram.
  • We will need to decide on how to model school. Should it be a fixed effect, or a random effect?
  • Lets look at one more thing - the balance of the data across schools. Are schools all the same size? or is there a mixture of small and large schools?

  • Schools are not all the same size!
  • Some schools have a lot of students (over 50), some schools have less (less than 30).
  • Is there any relationship between the number of students in a school, and the MathAchieve scores?
## Investigate the number of students and mean score by school
ggplot(MathAchieve_dt[,list(.N,MeanMathAch=mean(MathAch)),by=School],
       aes(N,MeanMathAch)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()

  • I dont see a strong relationship there. Often we will see that the smaller cluster sizes (Schools with few students) have unstable means (really high or low values) compared to the school with a large number of students. Why would that be true?
    • Possible small schools arent as good (a true effect)
    • But also possible small samples high a large amount of sampling variation! If you only have 3 students, they might all be high or low achieving students just by chance. The school might not be good or bad, we just have a small sample size (from that school). If you have 50+ students, it is less likely to have all 50 be high or low just by chance aloneso the bigger schools generally have stable means, because we have more data for them. This phenomena is termed sampling variation, and this is one reason we need random effects models! The shrinkage from random effect terms will stabilize these estimates. A fixed effect term would not.

Standard Linear Model

  • Lets start with a standard linear model on this data.
  • In that case, we will need to decide how to handle the school variable. Should we ignore it and leave it out of the model? Or include it in the model as a fixed effect?
  • We already looked at the mean score by school in the prior graph. Now, lets fit a model with the other potential predictors without school. We can then aggregate the residuals across school.
  • By examining the residuals, we can see if there are trends in the outcome associated with School that are not accounted for by the covariates.
#### First fit our models
## Fit model without school
mod1lm <- lm(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES,
             data=MathAchieve_dt)
summary(mod1lm)

Confidence Intervals

  • The authors of the lme4 package provide a confint function to calculate confidence intervals
  • These can be Wald, profile likelihood based, or bootstrapped. You should get similar results across these different methods. There are disagreements in the statistical literature on which method is best, so I present all three here for completeness.
  • you will notice the bootstrapped confidence intervals take a minute.
confint(mod2lmer,method="Wald")

Random Effects P Values?

  • P Values are intentionally excluded by default in lme4
  • This is due to the complexities associated with calculating p-values. The authors felt they should not be easily available without considering those complexities!
  • The lmerTest package overides some methods in lme4 and adds in p-values parallel to the p values calculated in other software.
library(lmerTest)
## add in fixed effects
mod2lmer <- lmer(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES + (1|School),
                 data=MathAchieve)
summary(mod2lmer)

Intraclass Correlation Coefficient

  • One way to summarize and contextualize the random intercept components in this sort of model is called the intraclass correlation coefficient. The idea is to describe the size of the variance component fit from the random intercept as a proportion of the total variance.
  • We might interpret this quantity by saying The proportion of variance explained by the grouping structure in the population.
  • For this problem, we would explain it as the proportion of variance in achievement scores explained by school.
  • Lets re-examine the first random intercept model and use it to calculate the ICC.
## Just a single random effect
mod1lmer <- lmer(MathAch ~ (1|School),
               data=MathAchieve_dt)
summary(mod1lmer)

##    Data: MathAchieve_dt

##

Random Slopes

  • Is it possible that at some schools, the relationship between SES and Math scores is lower or higher than at other schools?
  • Stated differentlyperhaps SES really matters for predicting math scores for some schools. But at other schools, the relationship is less important?
  • How would we model this without random effects?
  • We would need a different interaction term for every school!
  • That means a different slope estimate for each school.
## Here is the code to fit the ineraction. 
##How many predictors did I just put into the model...?
mod3lm <- 
  lm(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES*School,
     data=MathAchieve_dt)
## Can you interpret these results?

Random Slopes in lme4

  • We can add in random slopes by specifying the effect, then the cluster
  • We will get shrinkage estimates for the slopes in this case.
  • We are still estimating a slope for each school, but they are going to be shrunk towards the mean slope across all schools.
## Fit model with random intercept and slope
mod3lmer <- 
  lmer(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES + (1|School) + 
         (0+SES|School),
       data=MathAchieve)
## Equivalent way to fit the model
mod3lmer <- 
  lmer(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES + (SES||School),
       data=MathAchieve)
summary(mod3lmer)

Random Slope, Intercept, and Correlation between them

  • Another layer of complexity that can be added to these sort of random effects models is the correlation between random effects.
  • In the prior model we just fit, we assumed there was no correlation between the random intercept and the random slope. However, what if we suspected that schools with a higher baseline test score also had a higher relationship between SES and test scores?
  • It is possible that clusters with high intercepts tend to have high slopes (or some other relationship between random effects)
  • We can model this by estimating the actual correlation between the random intercept and random slope. The syntax is subtleif we use the single |, we are allowing correlations between random effects. If we use the ||, we are not.
mod4lmer <- lmer(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES + (SES|School),
           data=MathAchieve_dt)
summary(mod4lmer)

  • Can you interpret this graph? What do you think about the relationship between the slope and intercept?

  • It looks like the higher the schools average math achievement score, the smaller the effect of SES on math achievement. Why would that be?

    • Possibly average SES is very important at lower performing schools, but less important at higher performing schools. This could be related to financial resources of the schoolthe lowest performing schools may have the least financial resources, and the SES of the students family matters. But the higher performing schools may have more financial resources, so the SES of the students family matters less. Just a hypothesis!

Prediction from Random Effects Models

  • Lets try to make some predictions from our model
  • We may be interested in making marginal predictions (with respect to the random effects)
  • Or we may be interested in making predictions conditional on random effects (conditional on a school here).
  • The difference is whether or not we want to make the prediction for the average student at any school (marginal), or the student at a specific school (conditional)
## Prediction Dataframe
mod4lmer <- 
  lmer(MathAch ~ Minority + Sex + SES + (SES|School),
       data=MathAchieve_dt)
## School 7688,8627, 9586
pred_df <- 
  expand.grid(Minority="Yes",Sex="Male",SES=c(-1,0,1),
            School=c(7688,8627,9586))
pred_df$Achieve_pred_conditional <- 
  predict(mod4lmer,pred_df)
pred_df$Achieve_pred_marginal <- 
  predict(mod4lmer,pred_df,re.form=NA)
pred_df

lme4 Prediction Confidence Intervals

  • Confidence intervals are tricky to calculate, with disagreement on how to calculate them
  • The authors of lme4 suggest a bootstrapping approach, although this can be time consuming in bigger data sets
  • Another package, called merTools, has a function for prediction intervals
  • This function attempts to capture the uncertainty of both fixed effects and random effects
library(merTools)
predictInterval(mod4lmer,pred_df)

Logistic Regression with Random Intercept

  • Now lets add a random intercept for each school. This is just like we learned before - we are now adding a shrinkage effect to estimate the school level effect. This is summarized as a single variance component for each school (variance due to school).
  • Recall that logistic regression is a bit more complicated thoughwe need to think about whether we are working on the scale of the betas (right side of equation), or the scale of the outcome (left side - the probability of the event occuring).
  • These effects are generally interpreted on the scale of the betas, just like a regular logistic regression.
## Fit random intercept model by school
glmer_mod1 <- glmer(MathAch_bin ~ (1|School),
                    data=MathAchieve_dt,
                    family=binomial)
summary(glmer_mod1)

Calculating ICC with a Logistic Regression

  • Did you notice there is no residual variance in any of these logistic regression models? Why is that?

  • Remember - there is no sigma in a regular logistic regression! It uses the binomial distribution, where the variance is equal to \(np(1-p)\)

  • So how do we calculate the ICC? According to one reference, the residual variance is fixed at \((pi ^2) / 3\) thus, we can calculate ICC according to: \(intercept\_variance / (intercept\_variance + (pi ^2) / 3)\)

Moineddin, R., Matheson, F. I., & Glazier, R. H. (2007). A simulation study of sample size for multilevel logistic regression models. BMC Medical Research Methodology, 7, 34

## Calculate ICC 
VarCorr(glmer_mod1)
##  Groups Name        Std.Dev.
##  School (Intercept) 0.8649
0.8649 / (0.8649  + (pi ^2)/3)
## [1] 0.2081705

Conclusion

Random effects modeling are a mathematically complex extension to regular linear regression. However, the simple assumptions of linear regression are sometimes violated and we must model the variance structures to get appropriate p-values. Additionally, we may be interested in the shrinkage effect of a random term if that fits the contextual framework of the situation.
